Supper Club Market is expanding and opening a second location in Midlothian this winter.

The Tuckahoe prepared foods and provisions market is a local favorite and, answering the need for a similar market across town, owner Carlisle Bannister signed a lease on a new building on the Promenade in Winterfield at 14010-14030 Winterfield Lane.

The new location will carry the same products, like prepared meals, charcuterie, wine and beer, local boutique groceries, bakery items and fresh produce. The new location will also have the addition of a deli selling made-to-order deli sandwiches, which is something different from the offerings at the existing location.

“The lion share of our model is prepared foods,” said Bannister. “We have hundreds of prepared food items that we make from scratch in our kitchens. Everything from composed salads to full meal entrees, to a la carte side items, to provisions like pimento cheese, chicken salad and three different kinds of ham biscuits—that’s our specialty. In our new location, we’re going to have a gourmet deli with made-to-order deli sandwiches. We do not have that in our current location.”

The new location will also reflect the Tuckahoe location’s interior design scheme with cement floors, industrial exposed ceilings and ductwork, with lots of black and white décor, with bright accents throughout.

“We had the lease signed over there and we are getting ready to begin our build out any day now. We literally just inked the deal with the contractors, developers, and landlords. There have been rumors about our second location floating around for a while,” said Bannister.

What to ask for when you go to either location? Bannister said, “Our number one seller is chicken piccata. We also sell two different kinds of lasagna and we rotate the menu seasonally. Right now, we’re doing a bistro steak dinner with béarnaise sauce, roasted vegetables and potatoes. We also have blackened salmon with couscous, a Caprese chicken meal with roasted vegetables and grilled Mahi Mahi with a tomato hollandaise with Edwards ham and succotash.”

Bannister said that peoples' dining and eating habits changed post-COVID, which increased Supper Club's popularity.

“They just really appreciate a restaurant-quality meal that they can prepare. I think it was a necessity during COVID to eat like that, and I think they came to appreciate it and they kept on eating like that. It’s great for us,” he said.

For Bannister, winter of 2025 can’t get here soon enough. “We’re super excited about bringing a market to the Midlothian area. We’ve got a lot of folks that have visited this store and expressed an interest and a need for something like this over on that side of town.”
